<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Market Ends Lower as MCI Announces
   $1.25 Billion Buy-Out of Telecom USA
   ----
   By Anne Newman and Craig S. Smith
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Over-the-counter stocks barely budged in light trading as
some investors headed home early to begin celebrating
Passover and others prepared for a day off on Good Friday.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index of OTC stocks edged down just
0.72, or 0.17%, to close at 430.18. Heavy trading in MCI
Communications, which fell 1 1/8 to 35 3/4 after announcing
it would pay $42 a share, or $1.25 billion, for long-distance
carrier Telecom USA, helped flatten the index.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Trading is expected to be light all week because of the
two religious holidays. "I expect a quiet week and don't see
any big swings," said Peter DaPuzzo, head of OTC trading for
Shearson Lehman Hutton. "As traders, we'll provide our normal
liquidity, but I don't expect people to be aggressive or go
out on a limb on a week like this."
   OTC indexes are market weighted, magnifying the effect of
MCI's drop on the overall market. The New York Stock Exchange
composite index closed about 0.3% higher.
   OTC decliners led advancers 850 to 1,014. National Market
System volume fell to 84,575,100 shares, compared with
Friday's 102,138,400 shares. Trading in MCI accounted for
more than 3.4 million shares.
   MCI's announcement sparked excitement in another regional
telecommunications concern, Advanced Telecommunications.
Shares of the Atlanta-based company jumped 24% in sympathy
with Telecom to close up 3 1/4 at 16 3/4, on about 586,000
shares, or 10 times normal volume.
   Advanced Telecommunications is the nation's second largest
regional long-distance carrier, behind Telecom, in an
industry facing a "hot-bed" of consolidation, according to
analyst Mark Dunkel of Robinson-Humphrey Co.
   Mr. Dunkel says that Advanced Telecommunications looks
particularly attractive in light of the nearly 100% premium
MCI will pay for Telecom, or a multiple of 26 times his
estimate of Telecom's 1990 earnings.
   Before yesterday's gain, Advanced Telecommunications was
trading at just under 10 times Mr. Dunkel's estimated
earnings for the company of $1.40 a share for fiscal 1991,
ending in March. The company has a "very valuable" customer
base in Florida, Georgia and Texas and will be one to keep an
eye on amid continuing consolidation of regional long
distance carriers, Mr. Dunkel says.
   Several stocks that recently took a beating rebounded in
robust trading. Among them were Novell, up 1 1/4 at 40, which
tumbled 4 1/8 Friday after Lotus Development agreed to
acquire the company for stock. Also recovering in brisk
trading was Oracle Systems, which rose 3/4 to 16. Both stocks
were "oversold" last week, but regained favor yesterday, said
Jerry Newman, a San Francisco-based institutional salesman
with Cowen &amp; Co.
   Also on the active list, 3Com, added 1/8 at 13 3/8 after
announcing that it will buy back up to one million common
shares, or about 3.5% of its outstanding common stock.
   Michael Foods fell 1 1/4 to 13 7/8. Dain Bosworth lowered
its 1990 and 1991 earnings estimates for the company because
of its recently completed acquisition of the remaining 50% of
Milton G. Waldbaum Co. that it didn't previously own,
according to Dow Jones Professional Investor Report. Michael
Foods said it doesn't expect the acquisition to dilute
earnings.
</TEXT>
