<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                        CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Rohm &amp; Haas Co.'s Rohm &amp; Haas Holdings Ltd. -- $150
million issue of amortizing debentures, due April 15, 2020,
priced at par to yield 9.80%. The noncallable debentures,
priced at a spread of 1.25 percentage points above the
Treasury's 30-year bond, have an average life of 20.5 years
and are guaranteed by Rohm &amp; Haas. Rated single-A-1 by
Moody's Investors Service Inc. and single-A by Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp., the issue will be sold through Goldman Sachs &amp;
Co.
                                                                                                       

                          MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
real estate mortgage investment conduit securities in 23
classes through Nomura Securities International Inc. The
issue, series 1990-52, is backed by Fannie Mae 10 1/2%
securities.
                                                                                                       

                          EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   World Bank (agency) -- 45 billion yen ($285.3 million) of
7 1/4% Eurobonds due April 27, 1995, priced at 101 3/8 to
yield 7.31% less fees via IBJ International. Fees 1 5/8.
   European Investment Bank (agency) -- 150 million Swiss
francs ($100 million) of 7 1/2% privately placed notes due
May 4, 2000, priced at 101 3/8 to yield 7.30% via J.P. Morgan
Securities (Switzerland). Fees 2 1/8.
   Council of Europe (agency) -- 10 billion yen ($63.4
million) of floating-rate notes due April 26, 2000, paying
interest at 0.40 point below the long-term prime rate,
semiannually, priced at par via Daiwa Europe Ltd. Call option
in April 1991 at 100.20 and thereafter annually at par.
Once-only put option after seven years at par. Fees 0.25.
   Dai-Ichi Kangyo Australia Ltd. (Japanese parent) -- $50
million of Eurobonds due May 12, 2000, priced at 102 via DKB
International. Bonds pay interest at 0.33 point above
six-month London interbank offered rate for the first four
years; thereafter, fixed interest rate of 10%. Once-only call
option at par in 1994. Guaranteed by Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank.
Fees 2.
                                                                                                       

                            OTHER
                                                                                                       

   Student Loan Marketing Association -- $500 million of
floating-rate notes due Oct. 11, 1990, priced at par to yield
a variable rate equal to .20 percentage point above the
bond-equivalent yield of the three-month Treasury bill
auction rate.
</TEXT>
