<HL>
   Monday's Markets:
   Nail-Biting
   By Investors
   Sets Tone
   ---
   Dow Edges Up 4.95
   But Bonds Decline;
   Trading Is Uninspired
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Stock and bond prices moved in narrow ranges as investors
started a new week worried about first-quarter earnings and a
hefty new supply of government debt scheduled for auction
this week.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average edged up 4.95 points, to
2722.07. But declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange
were ahead of gainers and volume was anemic. Long-term
Treasury bond prices slipped in thin trading.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While currency traders scrambled to interpret the outcome
of the weekend meeting of the Group of Seven industrial
nations, neither bond nor stock investors were much
influenced by the dollar's gyrations. Instead, analysts said
investors in each market had enough to worry about without
trying to track the currency.
   The stock market's overriding concern remains
first-quarter earnings. Last week, bank stocks were hammered
by prospects of disappointing quarterly results, providing a
preview of what is in store for companies that surprise
shareholders with less-than-expected profits. Those stocks
rebounded somewhat yesterday after some analysts indicated
conditions affecting banks don't warrant the gloomy outlook.
   Nevertheless, the stock market probably has some rough
going ahead. Although analysts have been steadily revising
estimates of corporate earnings lower during recent weeks,
investors have reacted mostly with caution, standing pat with
their holdings rather than selling.
   One indication of the deep uncertainty afflicting
investors is that stock prices barely budged in New York
after a sharp rally in Tokyo. The Nikkei Index of 225 stocks
rose 1119.15, or 3.8%, to 30397.93 in a broad-based rally.
The best the Dow Jones Industrial Average could muster in
early trading yesterday was a gain of about 12 points, much
of it because of computer-assisted buy programs, that faded
later in the morning.
   Bond prices didn't fare as well. An early plunge in the
dollar in Far East trading set the stage for some selling as
trading opened in New York. But as the currency rebounded,
bond prices recouped some of their losses.
   The big factor overhanging the bond market, however, is
the auction today of $3.5 billion in Resolution Funding Corp.
40year bonds, followed tomorrow by the sale of $7.5 billion
in seven-year Treasury notes. Traders said prices fell
because market participants aren't sure how wellreceived the
two auctions will be.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices rose in light trading. Volume on the New York
Stock Exchange totaled 115.0 million shares. Declining issues
on the Big Board were ahead of gainers 839 to 652.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices were off. The Treasury's benchmark 30-year
bond fell a little more than a quarter of a point, or more
than $2.50 for each $1,000 face amount. The yield on the
issue rose to 8.54%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900410-0028
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900410-0028.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Takeover Lawyer Suggests
   Delay in Voting by Holders
</HL>
<DATE>
04/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<LP>
   With proxy fights proliferating, takeover defense lawyer
Martin Lipton has a new idea for companies worried about
their directors being voted out of office: don't let
shareholders vote as often.
   Mr. Lipton, a partner at Wachtell Lipton Rosen &amp; Katz,
suggests that directors ought to be elected to terms of five
years, instead of one or three, in what he calls a
"quinquennial system." Under his proposal, the annual meeting
would be eliminated, and shareholders would only meet every
five years.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Currently, most companies either elect all their directors
annually, or have staggered boards, with one-third up for
election each year. Staggered boards came into widespread use
early in the 1980s as an anti-takeover defense.
   "We need to strike a balance," Mr. Lipton said in a memo
to clients. "A balance that facilitates long-term planning by
corporations but does not entrench bad management." With such
a system, he added, "directors would run on the corporation's
record for the past five years and the corporation's
strategic plan for the next five years."
   However, Mr. Lipton acknowledged the idea would require
changes in state laws, federal securities laws and stock
exchange rules.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900410-0027
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900410-0027.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Centocor to Report
   Bacteria Drug Cuts
   Mortality Rates
   ----
   By Richard Koenig
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<CO>
   CNTO
</CO>
<IN>
DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)
</IN>
<LP>
   Centocor Inc. plans to report that its drug for treating
certain potentially fatal bacterial infections clearly
reduces mortality rates.
   According to a summary of a Centocor report to be made at
a scientific conference in May, the mortality rate fell 39%
when patients whose blood was infected with so-called
gram-negative bacteria were treated with the Centocor drug,
as against patients who receive a placebo. The summary calls
this reduction "highly significant" statistically.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Of 200 patients studied, 49% of those on the placebo died
within 28 days, while only 30% of those on the drug died.
Moreover, the summary says, the drug reduced mortality 42%
among those patients who had gone into septic shock.
   The summary was prepared as a help for the press at the
May conference but made available by the journal Clinical
Research. The lead investigator, Elizabeth Ziegler of the
University of California at San Diego, and Centocor officials
said they hadn't intended that the summary should be released
so soon and declined to comment. Clinical Research today will
publish the official, more technical abstract of the report
to be made in May.
   The summary, though sketchy on details, suggests how
Centocor, based in Malvern, Pa., hopes to answer a report by
rival Xoma Corp., issued last September. Like Centocor, Xoma,
based in Berkeley, Calif., is still seeking marketing
approval from the Food and Drug Administration for a drug to
treat gram-negative infections, which can follow abdominal
wounds, surgery and contamination of the catheters used in
hospitals.
   Any information divulged by the two biotechnology
companies is intensely scrutinized by Wall Street because
their similar products could be the first big-selling drugs
made from monoclonal antibodies, or proteins like those the
body produces naturally to fight disease. Mark Simon, an
analyst at Robertson Stephens &amp; Co., estimates that the U.S.
market for the drugs could total $350 million in 1993.
   According to some estimates, 200,000 people in the U.S.
develop gram-negative infections each year, and some 80,000
people die from them. The infections today are treated mostly
with antibiotics.
   The earlier report by Xoma indicated that its own drug,
for now called E5, also reduced mortality rates, but only
before patients entered what Xoma calls "severe refractory
shock," defined as sharply lower blood pressure and other
conditions. Yesterday, Patrick Scannon, Xoma's president,
noted that the summary of the Centocor study doesn't explain
how it defined shock -- a key part of the scientific debate.
   Dr. Scannon also noted that the Centocor study, at least
as presented in the summary, looked only at patients whose
blood was infected. He said the Xoma study had looked also at
other types of infection by gram-negative bacteria and so
that study is difficult to compare with the Centocor study.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900410-0026
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900410-0026.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- BayBanks Inc.:
   Bank-Holding Firm Reports
   A Deficit for First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
04/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<CO>
   BBNK
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   BayBanks Inc., Boston, reported a first-quarter loss of
$13.8 million, or 87 cents a share, in line with its previous
projections, after providing $68 million for possible loan
losses in the quarter.
   In the year-earlier quarter, the bank-holding company had
net income of $20.8 million, or $1.30 a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company said nonperforming loans and other real estate
owned totaled about $246 million, up from $156 million at
year end. Other loans 90 days or more past due were $100
million at March 31, down $14 million from Dec. 31. It said
reserves at March 31 equaled 52% of nonperforming loans and
other real estate owned.
   Separately, BayBanks said a holder has filed a lawsuit
against the company, its directors and certain officers in
federal court in Boston, charging that the company made
misleading disclosures in past public statements and reports.
Chairman William M. Crozier Jr. said "BayBanks believes that
it has reported its affairs properly and will vigorously
defend against this complaint.
   In national over-the-counter trading, BayBanks closed at
$15.25, up $1.375.
</TEXT>
